# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: linear-actuators
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] An **actuator** is a component of a machine that produces force, torque, or displacement, when an electrical, pneumatic or hydraulic input is supplied to it in a system (called an **actuating system**).
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The effect is usually produced in a controlled way.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] An actuator translates a stimulus such as an input signal into the required form of mechanical energy.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] An actuator requires a control device (which provides control signal) and a source of energy.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The control signal is relatively low in energy and may be voltage, electric current, pneumatic, or hydraulic fluid pressure, or even human power.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] In the electric, hydraulic, and pneumatic sense, it is a form of automation or automatic control.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The displacement achieved is commonly linear or rotational, as exemplified by linear motors and rotary motors, respectively.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Rotary motion is more natural for small machines making large displacements.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] By means of a leadscrew, ball screw, or roller screw, rotary motion can be adapted to function as a linear actuator (which produces a linear motion, but is not a linear motor).
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Another broad classification of actuators separates them into two types: incremental-drive actuators and continuous-drive actuators.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Stepper motors are one type of incremental-drive actuators.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Examples of continuous-drive actuators include DC torque motors, induction motors, hydraulic and pneumatic motors, and piston-cylinder drives (rams).
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] An actuator can be just a mechanism that is directly driven by the motions or forces of other parts of the system.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] An example is the camshafts that drive the intake and exhaust valves in internal combustion engines, driven by the engine itself.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Another example is the mechanism that strikes the hours in a traditional grandfather clock or cuckoo clock.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] A hydraulic actuator typically uses the pressure of a liquid (usually oil) to cause a piston to slide inside a hollow cylindrical tube into linear, rotary, or oscillatory motion.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] In a *single acting* actuator the fluid pressure is applied to just one side of the piston, so that it applies useful force in only one direction.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The opposite motion may be affected by a spring, by gravity, or by other forces present in the system.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] In a *double acting* actuator, the return stroke is driven by fluid pressure applied to the opposite side of the piston.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Since liquids are nearly impossible to compress, a hydraulic actuator can exert a large force.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The drawback of this approach is its limited acceleration.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] They respond quickly to input changes, have little inertia, can operate continuously over a relatively large working range, and can hold their position without any significant energy input.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] A hydraulic actuator can be used to displace the rack of a rack and pinion mechanism, causing the pinion to turn.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] This arrangement is used, for example, to operate valves in pipelines and other industrial fluid transport installations.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] A pneumatic actuator is similar to a hydraulic one but uses a gas (usually air) instead of a liquid.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Compared to hydraulic actuators, pneumatic ones are less complicated because they do not need pipes for the return and recycling of the working fluid.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] On the other hand, they still need external infrastructure such as compressors, reservoirs, filters, and air treatment subsystems, which often makes them less convenient than electrical or electromechanical actuators.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] In the first steam engines and in all steam locomotives, steam pressure is used to drive pneumatic actuators to produce a reciprocating motion, which is converted to rotary motion by some sort of crankshaft mechanism.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Since 1960, several actuator technologies have been developed.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] An electric actuator typically uses an electric motor to generate torque, which is then converted into linear or rotary motion to drive a mechanical system.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] An electromechanical actuator (EMA) uses mechanical means to convert the rotational force of an ordinary (rotary) electric motor into a linear movement.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The mechanism may be a toothed belt or a screw (either a ball or a lead screw or planetary roller screw).
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The main advantages of electromechanical actuators are their relatively good level of accuracy with respect to pneumatics, their possible long lifecycle and the little maintenance effort required (might require grease).
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] It is possible to reach relatively high force, on the order of 100 kN.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The main limitation of these actuators are the reachable speed, the important dimensions and weight they require.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The main application of such actuators is mainly seen in health care devices and factory automation.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Another approach is an electrohydraulic actuator, where the electric motor remains the prime mover but provides torque to operate a hydraulic accumulator that is then used to transmit actuation force in much the same way that diesel engine/hydraulics are typically used in heavy equipment.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Electrical energy is used to actuate equipment such as multi-turn valves, or electric-powered construction and excavation equipment.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] When used to control the flow of fluid through a valve, a brake is typically installed above the motor to prevent the fluid pressure from forcing open the valve.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] If no brake is installed, the actuator gets activated to reclose the valve, which is slowly forced open again.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] This sets up an oscillation (open, close, open ...) and the motor and actuator will eventually become damaged.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Electric rotary actuators use a rotary motor to turn the target part over a certain angle.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Rotary actuators can have up to a rotation of 360 degrees.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] This allows it to differ from a linear motor as the linear is bound to a set distance compared to the rotary motor.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Rotary motors have the ability to be set at any given degree in a field making the device easier to set up still with durability and a set torque.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Rotary motors can be powered by 3 different techniques such as Electric, Fluid, or Manual.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] However, Fluid powered rotary actuators have 5 sub-sections of actuators such as Scotch Yoke, Vane, Rack-and-Pinion, Helical, and Electrohydraulic.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] All forms have their own specific design and use allowing the ability to choose multiple angles of degree.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Rotary actuators have numerous applications but are often found in hydraulic pressured devices and industries or tasks with motion control systems.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Rotary actuators are even used in robotic arms in industry lines.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] A linear electric actuator uses a linear motor, which can be thought as a rotary electric motor which has been cut and unrolled.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Thus, instead of producing a rotational movement, it produces a linear force along their length.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Because it generally has lower friction losses than the alternatives, a linear electric actuator can last over a hundred million cycles.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Linear motors are divided in 3 basic categories: flat linear motor (classic), U-Channel linear motors and Tubular linear motors.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Linear motor technology is the best solution in the context of a low load (up to 30Kg) because it provides the highest level of speed, control and accuracy.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] In fact, it represents the most desired and versatile technology.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Due to the limitations of pneumatics, the current electric actuator technology is a viable solution for specific industry applications and it has been successfully introduced in market segments such as the watchmaking, semiconductor and pharmaceutical industries (as high as 60% of the applications.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] An actuator may be driven by heat through the expansion that most solid material exhibit when the temperature increases.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] This principle is commonly used, for example, to operate electric switches in thermostats.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Typically, a (non-electronic) thermostat contains a strip with two layers of different metals, that will bend when heated.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Thermal actuators may also exploit the properties of shape-memory alloys.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Some actuators are driven by externally applied magnetic fields.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] They typically contain parts made of ferromagnetic materials that are strongly attracted to each other when they are magnetized by the external field.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] An example are the reed switches that may be used as door opening sensors in a building security system.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Alternatively, magnetic actuators can use magnetic shape-memory alloys.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] A soft actuator is made of a flexible material that changes its shape in response to stimuli including mechanical, thermal, magnetic, and electrical.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Soft actuators mainly deal with the robotics of humans rather than industry which is what most of the actuators are used for.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] For most actuators they are mechanically durable yet do not have an ability to adapt compared to soft actuators.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The soft actuators apply to mainly safety and healthcare for humans which is why they are able to adapt to environments by disassembling their parts.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated using multistep low yield processes such as micro-moulding, solid freeform fabrication, and mask lithography.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] However, these methods require manual fabrication of devices, post processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until maturity in the fabrication is achieved.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] To avoid the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Therefore, special soft systems that can be fabricated in a single step by rapid prototyping methods, such as 3D printing, are utilized to narrow the gap between the design and implementation of soft actuators, making the process faster, less expensive, and simpler.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Shape memory polymer (SMP) actuators are the most similar to our muscles, providing a response to a range of stimuli such as light, electrical, magnetic, heat, pH, and moisture changes.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] They have some deficiencies including fatigue and high response time that have been improved through the introduction of smart materials and combination of different materials by means of advanced fabrication technology.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The advent of 3D printers has made a new pathway for fabricating low-cost and fast response SMP actuators.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The process of receiving external stimuli like heat, moisture, electrical input, light or magnetic field by SMP is referred to as shape memory effect (SME).
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] SMP exhibits some rewarding features such a low density, high strain recovery, biocompatibility, and biodegradability.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Photopolymers or light activated polymers (LAP) are another type of SMP that are activated by light stimuli.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The LAP actuators can be controlled remotely with instant response and, without any physical contact, only with the variation of light frequency or intensity.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] A need for soft, lightweight and biocompatible soft actuators in soft robotics has influenced researchers for devising pneumatic soft actuators because of their intrinsic compliance nature and ability to produce muscle tension.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Polymers such as dielectric elastomers (DE), ionic polymer–metal composites (IPMC), ionic electroactive polymers, polyelectrolyte gels, and gel-metal composites are common materials to form 3D layered structures that can be tailored to work as soft actuators.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] EAP actuators are categorized as 3D printed soft actuators that respond to electrical excitation as deformation in their shape.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] In engineering, actuators are frequently used as mechanisms to introduce motion, or to clamp an object so as to prevent motion.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] In electronic engineering, actuators are a subdivision of transducers.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] They are devices which transform an input signal (mainly an electrical signal) into some form of motion.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Rotary motors are primarily used when rotational motion is required, but can also be used for linear applications by transforming rotary motion into linear motion with a lead screw or similar mechanism.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] On the other hand, some actuators are intrinsically linear, such as piezoelectric actuators.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] In virtual instrumentation, actuators and sensors are the hardware complements of virtual instruments.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Performance metrics for actuators include speed, acceleration, and force (alternatively, angular speed, angular acceleration, and torque), as well as energy efficiency and considerations such as mass, volume, operating conditions, and durability, among others.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] When considering force in actuators for applications, two main metrics should be considered.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Static load is the force capability of the actuator while not in motion.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Conversely, the dynamic load of the actuator is the force capability while in motion.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Speed should be considered primarily at a no-load pace, since the speed will invariably decrease as the load amount increases.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] The rate the speed will decrease will directly correlate with the amount of force and the initial speed.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Actuators are commonly rated using the standard IP Code rating system.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] Those that are rated for dangerous environments will have a higher IP rating than those for personal or common industrial use.
[src:linear-actuators/actuator] This will be determined by each individual manufacturer, depending on usage and quality.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] A **ball screw** (or **ballscrew**) is a mechanical linear actuator that translates rotational motion to linear motion with little friction.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] A threaded shaft provides a helical raceway for ball bearings which act as a precision screw.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] As well as being able to apply or withstand high thrust loads, they can do so with minimum internal friction.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] They are made to close tolerances and are therefore suitable for high-precision applications.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The ball assembly acts as the nut while the threaded shaft is the screw.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] In contrast to conventional leadscrews, ball screws tend to be rather bulky, due to the need to have a mechanism to recirculate the balls.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The ball screw was invented independently by H.M.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Glenn who were issued in 1898 patents 601,451 and 610,044 respectively.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Early precise screwshafts were produced by starting with a low-precision screwshaft, and then lapping the shaft with several spring-loaded nut laps..
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] By rearranging and inverting the nut laps, the lengthwise errors of the nuts and shaft were averaged.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Then, the repeatable pitch shaft's pitch is measured against a distance standard.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] A similar process is sometimes used today to produce reference standard screw shafts and to master manufacturing screw shafts.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Low friction in ball screws yields high mechanical efficiency compared to alternatives.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] A typical ball screw may be 90 percent efficient, versus 20 to 25 percent efficiency of an Acme lead screw of equal size.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Lack of sliding friction between the nut and screw lends itself to extended lifespan of the screw assembly (especially in no-backlash systems), reducing downtime for maintenance and parts replacement, while also decreasing demand for lubrication.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] This, combined with their overall performance benefits and reduced power requirements, may offset the initial costs of using ball screws.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Ball screws may also reduce or eliminate the backlash common in lead screw and nut combinations.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The balls may be preloaded so that there is no "wiggle" between the ball screw and ball nut.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] This is particularly desirable in applications where the load on the screw varies quickly, such as machine tools.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Because of their high mechanical efficiency, especially compared to traditional lead screws, ball screws can potentially be back-driven (that is, a linear force applied directly to the nut can induce a rotation of the shaft, an effect counterproductive to most uses).
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] While this is usually of limited consequence to motorized applications, and potentially even provides a mild protective effect in some cases, it makes them generally unsuitable for application in manually actuated systems, such as hand-fed machine tools.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The static torque and digital control of an appropriate servomotor can be made to resist and compensate, but hand cranked mechanisms would require additional mechanisms to prevent undesirable behaviors.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Because an ordinary lead screw resists or even prohibits such reverse operation, they are inherently safer and more reliable for manual use.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The magnitude of force needed to consequentially back-drive an Acme lead screw would usually be sufficient to destroy the mechanism, immobilizing the machine and absorbing any dangerous force before it could pose a risk to an operator.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The circulating balls travel inside the thread form of the screw and nut, and balls are recirculated through various types of return mechanisms.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] If the ball nut did not have a return mechanism, then the balls would fall out of the end of the ball nut when they reached the end of the nut.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] For this reason several different recirculation methods have been developed.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] An *external ballnut* employs a stamped tube which picks up balls from the raceway by use of a small pick-up finger.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Balls travel inside the tube and are then replaced back into the thread raceway.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] An *internal-button ballnut* employs a machined or cast button-style return which allows balls to exit the raceway track and move one thread then reenter the raceway.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] An *endcap return ball* nut employs a cap on the end of the ball nut.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The cap is machined to pick up balls coming out of the end of the nut and direct them down holes which are bored transversely down the ballnut.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The complement cap on the other side of the nut directs balls back into the raceway.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The returning balls are not under significant mechanical load and the return path may incorporate injection-moulded low-friction plastic parts.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] A ball screw involves significantly more parts and surface interactions than many similar systems.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] While a basic lead screw is composed of only a solid shaft and a solid nut with simple mating geometries, a ball screw requires precisely formed curved contours and multi-part assemblies to facilitate the action of the bearing balls.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] This makes them more expensive to manufacture and sometimes to maintain, and provides more potential avenues for failure if the apparatus is not properly cared for.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] if the linear force is backdriving the system.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] In these equations, ${\mathit {T}}$ is the torque applied to screw or nut, ${\mathit {F}}$ is the linear force applied, ${\mathit {l}}$ is the ball screw lead, and $\nu$ is the ball screw efficiency.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Selection of the standard to be used is an agreement between the supplier and the user and has some significance in the design of the screw.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] In the United States, ASME has developed the B5.48-1977 Standard entitled "Ball Screws".
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The correct evaluation of the curvatures of ball screw grooves allows one to accurately design the constructive parameters of this mechanism and to enhance its performance.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The formulation commonly used in literature refers to the ball bearing's geometry, ignoring the shape of the section's profile and the helix angle.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The second principal curvature is simply $\kappa _{2s}=-{\frac {1}{2f_{s}r_{b}}}$ for the screw shaft groove and $\kappa _{2n}=-{\frac {1}{2f_{n}r_{b}}}$ for the nut groove, where $f_{s}$ and $f_{n}$ are, respectively, the conformity factors of the groove profiles of the screw shaft and nut.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] These formulations do not take into account the shape of the groove profiles and the presence of the helix angle: more recent publications found the exact solution for the curvature of the grooves of screw shaft and nut.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] A new research proposes a new formulation which approximates the real curvature values with a maximum relative error of approximately 0.5%.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] To maintain their inherent accuracy and ensure long life, great care is needed to avoid contamination with dirt and abrasive particles.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] This may be achieved by using rubber or leather bellows to completely or partially enclose the working surfaces.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Another solution is to use a positive pressure of filtered air when they are used in a semi-sealed or open enclosure.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] While reducing friction, ball screws can operate with some preload, effectively eliminating backlash (slop) between input (rotation) and output (linear motion).
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] This feature is essential when they are used in computer-controlled motion-control systems, such as CNC machine tools and high precision motion applications (such as wire bonding).
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] To obtain proper rolling action of the balls, as in a standard ball bearing, it is necessary that, when loaded in one direction, the ball makes contact at one point with the nut, and one point with the screw.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] In practice, most ball screws are designed to be lightly preloaded, so that there is at least a slight load on the ball at four points, two in contact with the nut and two in contact with the screw.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] To this end, the threads are usually machined as a "gothic arch" profile.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] If a simple semicircular thread profile were used, contact would only be at two points, on the outer and inner edges, which would not resist axial loading.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] To remove backlash and obtain the optimum stiffness and wear characteristics for a given application, a controlled amount of preload is usually applied.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] This is accomplished in some cases by machining the components such that the balls are a "tight" fit when assembled; however, this gives poor control of the preload, and cannot be adjusted to allow for wear.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Ball screw shafts may be fabricated by rolling, yielding a less precise but inexpensive and mechanically efficient product.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Rolled ball screws have a positional precision of several thousandths of an inch per foot.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Ball screws are classified using "accuracy grades" from C0 (most precise) to C10.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] High-precision screw shafts are typically precise to one thousandth of an inch per foot (830 nm/cm) or better.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] They have historically been machined to gross shape, case-hardened, and then ground.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The three-step process is needed because high-temperature machining distorts the workpiece.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Hard whirling is a recent (2008) precision machining technique that minimizes heating of the work, and can produce precision screws from case-hardened bar stock.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Instrument-quality screw shafts are typically precise to 250 nanometers per centimeter.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] They are produced on precision milling machines with optical distance measuring equipment and special tooling.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Similar machines are used to produce optical lenses and mirrors.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Instrument screw shafts are generally made of Invar, to prevent temperature from changing tolerances too much.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Ball screws are used in aircraft and missiles to move control surfaces, especially for electric fly by wire, and in automobile power steering to translate rotary motion from an electric motor to axial motion of the steering rack.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] They are also used in machine tools, robots, and precision assembly equipment.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] High-precision ball screws are used in steppers for semiconductor manufacturing.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] A ball screw is used to expand the Deployable Tower Assembly (DTA) structure on the James Webb Space Telescope.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] A ball screw is also planned to be used in TerraPower's Natrium Reactor as part of its Control rod drive mechanism.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] Another form of linear actuator based on a rotating rod is the threadless ballscrew, or "rolling ring drive".
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] In this design, three or more rolling-ring bearings are arranged symmetrically in a housing surrounding a smooth (threadless) actuator rod or shaft.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] The bearings are set at an angle to the rod, and this angle determines the direction and rate of linear motion per revolution of the rod.
[src:linear-actuators/ball-screw] An advantage of this design over the conventional ballscrew or leadscrew is the practical elimination of backlash and loading caused by preload nuts.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] A **leadscrew** (or **lead screw**), pronounced /liːd skruː/, also known as a **power screw** or **translation screw**, is a screw used as a linkage in a machine, to translate turning motion into linear motion.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Because of the large area of sliding contact between their male and female members, screw threads have larger frictional energy losses compared to other linkages.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] They are not typically used to carry high power, but more for intermittent use in low power actuator and positioner mechanisms.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Leadscrews are commonly used in linear actuators, machine slides (such as in machine tools), vises, presses, and jacks.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] The word "lead" – pronounced /liːd/, from the verb "to lead" – refers to the amount of distance travelled per rotation, not the metal.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Leadscrews are manufactured in the same way as other thread forms: they may be rolled, cut, or ground.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] A lead screw is sometimes used with a split nut (also called a half nut) which allows the nut to be disengaged from the threads and moved axially, independently of the screw's rotation, when needed (such as in single-point threading on a manual lathe).
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] A split nut can also be used to compensate for wear by compressing the parts of the nut.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Power screws are classified by the geometry of their thread.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] V-threads are less suitable for leadscrews than others such as Acme because they have more friction between the threads.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Their threads are designed to induce this friction to keep the fastener from loosening.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Leadscrews, on the other hand, are designed to minimize friction.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Therefore, in most commercial and industrial use, V-threads are avoided for leadscrew use.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Nevertheless, V-threads are sometimes successfully used as leadscrews, for example on microlathes and micromills.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Square threads are named after their square geometry.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] They are the most efficient, having the least friction, so they are often used for screws that carry high power; however, they are also the most difficult to machine, and are thus the most expensive.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Acme threads have a 29° thread angle, which is easier to machine than square threads.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] They are not as efficient as square threads, due to the increased friction induced by the thread angle.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Acme threads are generally also stronger than square threads due to their trapezoidal thread profile, which provides greater load-bearing capabilities.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Buttress threads are of a triangular shape.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] These are used where the load force on the screw is only applied in one direction.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] They are as efficient as square threads in these applications, but are easier to manufacture.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] The disadvantages are that most are not very efficient.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Due to this low efficiency, they cannot be used in continuous power transmission applications.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] They also have a high degree of friction on the threads, which can wear the threads out quickly.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] For square threads, the nut must be replaced; for trapezoidal threads, a split nut may be used to compensate for the wear.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] The torque required to lift or lower a load can be calculated by "unwrapping" one revolution of a thread.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] This is most easily described for a square or buttress thread as the thread angle is 0 and has no bearing on the calculations.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] The unwrapped thread forms a right angle triangle where the base is $\pi d_{\text{m}}$ long and the height is the lead (pictured to the right).
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Based on the $T_{\text{lower}}$ equation, it can be found that the screw is self-locking when the coefficient of friction is greater than the tangent of the lead angle.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] An equivalent comparison is when the friction angle is greater than the lead angle ( $\phi >\lambda$ ).
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] However, this self-locking property is not absolute.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] Under dynamic conditions—particularly in the presence of vibration or shock loading—the effective coefficient of friction may drop to dynamic levels (which are typically lower than static), allowing the screw to back-drive unexpectedly.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] For this reason, safety-critical applications often require a secondary holding brake rather than relying solely on the lead screw geometry.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] For screws that have a thread angle other than zero, such as a trapezoidal thread, this must be compensated as it increases the frictional forces.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] where $\alpha \,$ is one half the thread angle.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] If the leadscrew has a collar which the load rides on, then the frictional forces between the interface must be accounted for in the torque calculations as well.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] where $\mu _{\text{c}}$ is the coefficient of friction between the collar on the load and $d_{\text{c}}$ is the mean collar diameter.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] For collars that use thrust bearings, the frictional loss is negligible and the above equation can be ignored.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] The running speed for a leadscrew (or ball screw) is typically limited to, at most, 80% of the calculated critical speed.
[src:linear-actuators/leadscrew] The critical speed is the speed that excites the natural frequency of the screw.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] A **linear actuator** is an actuator that creates linear motion (i.e., in a straight line), in contrast to the circular motion of a conventional electric motor.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Linear actuators are used in machine tools and industrial machinery, in computer peripherals such as disk drives and printers, in valves and dampers, and in many other places where linear motion is required.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Hydraulic or pneumatic cylinders inherently produce linear motion.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Mechanical linear actuators typically operate by conversion of rotary motion into linear motion.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Some mechanical linear actuators only pull, such as hoists, chain drive and belt drives.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Others only push (such as a cam actuator).
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Pneumatic and hydraulic cylinders, or lead screws can be designed to generate force in both directions.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Mechanical actuators typically convert rotary motion of a control knob or handle into linear displacement via screws and/or gears to which the knob or handle is attached.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] A jackscrew or car jack is a familiar mechanical actuator.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Another family of actuators are based on the segmented spindle.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Rotation of the jack handle is converted mechanically into the linear motion of the jack head.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Mechanical actuators are also frequently used in the field of lasers and optics to manipulate the position of linear stages, rotary stages, mirror mounts, goniometers and other positioning instruments.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] For accurate and repeatable positioning, index marks may be used on control knobs.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Some actuators include an encoder and digital position readout.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] These are similar to the adjustment knobs used on micrometers except their purpose is position adjustment rather than position measurement.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Hydraulic actuators or hydraulic cylinders typically involve a hollow cylinder having a piston inserted in it.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] An unbalanced pressure applied to the piston generates a force that can move an external object.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Since liquids are nearly incompressible, a hydraulic cylinder can provide controlled, precise linear displacement of the piston.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The displacement is only along the axis of the piston.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] A familiar example of a manually operated hydraulic actuator is a hydraulic car jack.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Typically though, the term "hydraulic actuator" refers to a device controlled by a hydraulic pump.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Pneumatic actuators, or pneumatic cylinders, are similar to hydraulic actuators except they use compressed air to generate force instead of a liquid.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] They work similarly to a piston in which air is pumped inside a chamber and pushed out of the other side of the chamber.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Air actuators are not necessarily used for heavy duty machinery and instances where large amounts of weight are present.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] One of the reasons pneumatic linear actuators are preferred to other types is the fact that the power source is simply an air compressor.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Because air is the input source, pneumatic actuators are able to be used in many places of mechanical activity.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The downside is, most air compressors are large, bulky, and loud.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] They are hard to transport to other areas once installed.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Pneumatic linear actuators are likely to leak and this makes them less efficient than mechanical linear actuators.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The piezoelectric effect is a property of certain materials in which application of a voltage to the material causes it to expand.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Very high voltages correspond to only tiny expansions.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] As a result, piezoelectric actuators can achieve extremely fine positioning resolution, but also have a very short range of motion.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] In addition, piezoelectric materials exhibit hysteresis which makes it difficult to control their expansion in a repeatable manner.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Electro-mechanical actuators are similar to mechanical actuators except that the control knob or handle is replaced with an electric motor.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Rotary motion of the motor is converted to linear displacement.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Electromechanical actuators may also be used to power a motor that converts electrical energy into mechanical torque.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] There are many designs of modern linear actuators and every company that manufactures them tends to have a proprietary method.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The following is a generalized description of a very simple electro-mechanical linear actuator.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Typically, an electric motor is mechanically connected to rotate a lead screw.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] A lead screw has a continuous helical thread machined on its circumference running along the length (similar to the thread on a bolt).
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Threaded onto the lead screw is a lead nut or ball nut with corresponding helical threads.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The nut is prevented from rotating with the lead screw (typically the nut interlocks with a non-rotating part of the actuator body).
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] When the lead screw is rotated, the nut will be driven along the threads.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The direction of motion of the nut depends on the direction of rotation of the lead screw.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] By connecting linkages to the nut, the motion can be converted to usable linear displacement.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Most current actuators are built for high speed, high force, or a compromise between the two.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] When considering an actuator for a particular application, the most important specifications are typically travel, speed, force, accuracy, and lifetime.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Most varieties are mounted on dampers or butterfly valves.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] There are many types of motors that can be used in a linear actuator system.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] These include dc brush, dc brushless, stepper, or in some cases, induction motors.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] It all depends on the application requirements and the loads the actuator is designed to move.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] For example, a linear actuator using an integral horsepower AC induction motor driving a lead screw can be used to operate a large valve in a refinery.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] In this case, accuracy and high movement resolution aren't needed, but high force and speed are.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] For electromechanical linear actuators used in laboratory instrumentation robotics, optical and laser equipment, or X-Y tables, fine resolution in the micron range and high accuracy may require the use of a fractional horsepower stepper motor linear actuator with a fine pitch lead screw.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] There are many variations in the electromechanical linear actuator system.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] It is critical to understand the design requirements and application constraints to know which one would be best.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] A linear actuator using standard motors will commonly have the motor as a separate cylinder attached to the side of the actuator, either parallel with the actuator or perpendicular to the actuator.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The motor may be attached to the end of the actuator.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The drive motor is of typical construction with a solid drive shaft that is geared to the drive nut or drive screw of the actuator.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Compact linear actuators use specially designed motors that try to fit the motor and actuator into the smallest possible shape.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] In the majority of linear actuator designs, the basic principle of operation is that of an inclined plane.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The threads of a lead screw act as a continuous ramp that allows a small rotational force to be used over a long distance to accomplish the movement of a large load over a short distance.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The power supply is from a DC or AC motor.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The typical motor is a 12 V DC, but other voltages are available.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Actuators have a switch to reverse the polarity of the motor, which makes the actuator change its motion.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The speed and force of an actuator depend on its gearbox.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The amount of force depends on the actuator’s speed.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Lower speeds supply greater force because motor speed and force are constant.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] One of the basic differences between actuators is their stroke, which is defined by the length of the screw and shaft.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Speed depends on the gears that connect the motor to the screw.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The mechanism to stop the stroke of an actuator is a limit or micro switch, which can be seen in the image below.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Microswitches are located at the top and bottom of the shaft and are triggered by the up and down movement of the screw.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Many variations on the basic design have been created.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Most focus on providing general improvements such as a higher mechanical efficiency, speed, or load capacity.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] There is also a large engineering movement towards actuator miniaturization.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Most electro-mechanical designs incorporate a lead screw and lead nut.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] In either case the screw may be connected to a motor or manual control knob either directly or through a series of gears.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Gears are typically used to allow a smaller (and weaker) motor spinning at a higher rpm to be geared down to provide the torque necessary to spin the screw under a heavier load than the motor would otherwise be capable of driving directly.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Effectively this sacrifices actuator speed in favor of increased actuator thrust.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] In some applications the use of worm gear is common as this allows a smaller built-in dimension still allowing great travel length.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] A traveling-nut linear actuator has a motor that stays attached to one end of the lead screw (perhaps indirectly through a gear box), the motor spins the lead screw, and the lead nut is restrained from spinning so it travels up and down the lead screw.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] A traveling-screw linear actuator has a lead screw that passes entirely through the motor.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] In a traveling-screw linear actuator, the motor "crawls" up and down a lead screw that is restrained from spinning.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The only spinning parts are inside the motor, and may not be visible from the outside.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Some lead screws have multiple "starts".
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] This means they have multiple threads alternating on the same shaft.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] One way of visualizing this is in comparison to the multiple color stripes on a candy cane.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] This allows for more adjustment between thread pitch and nut/screw thread contact area, which determines the extension speed and load carrying capacity (of the threads), respectively.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Linear screw actuators can have a static loading capacity, meaning that when the motor stops the actuator essentially locks in place and can support a load that is either pulling or pushing on the actuator.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] This static load capacity increases mobility and speed.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The braking force of the actuator varies with the angular pitch of the screw threads and the specific design of the threads.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Acme threads have a very high static load capacity, while ball screws have an extremely low load capacity and can be nearly free-floating.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Generally it is not possible to vary the static load capacity of screw actuators without additional technology.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The screw thread pitch and drive nut design defines a specific load capacity that cannot be dynamically adjusted.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] In some cases, high viscosity grease can be added to linear screw actuators to increase the static load.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Some manufacturers use this to alter the load for specific needs.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Static load capacity can be added to a linear screw actuator using an electromagnetic brake system, which applies friction to the spinning drive nut.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] For example, a spring may be used to apply brake pads to the drive nut, holding it in position when power is turned off.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] When the actuator needs to be moved, an electromagnet counteracts the spring and releases the braking force on the drive nut.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Similarly an electromagnetic ratchet mechanism can be used with a linear screw actuator so that the drive system lifting a load will lock in position when power to the actuator is turned off.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] To lower the actuator, an electromagnet is used to counteract the spring force and unlock the ratchet.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Dynamic load capacity is typically referred to as the amount of force the linear actuator is capable of providing during operation.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] This force will vary with screw type (amount of friction restricting movement) and the motor driving the movement.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Dynamic load is the figure which most actuators are classified by, and is a good indication of what applications it would suit best.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] In most cases when using an electro-mechanical actuator, it is preferred to have some type of speed control.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Such controllers vary the voltage supplied to the motor, which in turn changes the speed at which the lead screw turns.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Adjusting the gear ratio is another way to adjust speed.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Some actuators are available with several different gearing options.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] The duty cycle of a motor refers to the amount of time the actuator can be run before it needs to cool down.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Staying within this guideline when operating an actuator is key to its longevity and performance.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] If the duty cycle rating is exceeded, then overheating, loss of power, and eventual burning of the motor is risked.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] A linear motor is functionally the same as a rotary electric motor with the rotor and stator circular magnetic field components laid out in a straight line.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Where a rotary motor would spin around and re-use the same magnetic pole faces again, the magnetic field structures of a linear motor are physically repeated across the length of the actuator.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Since the motor moves in a linear fashion, no lead screw is needed to convert rotary motion to linear.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] While high capacity is possible, the material and/or motor limitations on most designs are surpassed relatively quickly due to a reliance solely on magnetic attraction and repulsion forces.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Most linear motors have a low load capacity compared to other types of linear actuators.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Linear motors have an advantage in outdoor or dirty environments in that the two halves do not need to contact each other, and so the electromagnetic drive coils can be waterproofed and sealed against moisture and corrosion, allowing for a very long service life.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Linear motors are being used extensively in high performance positioning systems for applications which require various combinations of high velocity, high precision and high force.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Telescoping linear actuators are specialized linear actuators used where space restrictions exist.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Their range of motion is many times greater than the unextended length of the actuating member.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] A common form is made of concentric tubes of approximately equal length that extend and retract like sleeves, one inside the other, such as the telescopic cylinder.
[src:linear-actuators/linear-actuator] Other more specialized telescoping actuators use actuating members that act as rigid linear shafts when extended, but break that line by folding, separating into pieces and/or uncoiling when retracted.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] A **rack and pinion** is a type of linear actuator that comprises a circular gear (the *pinion*) engaging a linear gear (the *rack*).
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] Together, they convert between rotational motion and linear motion: rotating the pinion causes the rack to be driven in a line.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] Conversely, moving the rack linearly will cause the pinion to rotate.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] The rack and pinion mechanism is used in rack railways, where the pinion mounted on a locomotive or a railroad car engages a rack usually placed between the rails, and helps to move the train up a steep gradient.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] It is also used in arbor presses and drill presses, where the pinion is connected to a lever and displaces a vertical rack (the **ram**).
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] In pipelines and other industrial piping systems, a rack displaced by a linear actuator turns a pinion to open or close a valve.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] Stairlifts, lock gates, electric gates, and the mechanical steering mechanism of cars are other notable applications.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] The term "rack and pinion" may be used also when the rack is not straight but **arcuate** (bent), namely just a section of a large gear.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] A single pinion can simultaneously drive two racks, parallel but opposite; which will always be displaced by the same distance, only in opposite directions.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] Conversely, by applying opposite forces to the two racks one can obtain pure torque on the pinion, without any force component.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] This **double rack and pinion** mechanism can be used, for example, with a pair of pneumatic actuators to operate a valve with minimum stress.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] The cranequin was a rack-and-pinion device used in the 15th century to draw back the string of a crossbow.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] In 1598, firearms designer Zhao Shizhen developed the Xuanyuan arquebus (軒轅銃), featuring a rack-and-pinion matchlock mechanism derived from an Ottoman Turkish matchlock design.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] The *Wu Pei Chih* (1621) later described Ottoman Turkish muskets that used a rack-and-pinion mechanism.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] The use of a variable rack (still using a normal pinion) was invented by Arthur Ernest Bishop in the 1970s, so as to improve vehicle response and steering "feel", especially at high speeds.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] He also created a low cost press forging process to manufacture the racks, eliminating the need to machine the gear teeth.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] A rack and pinion has roughly the same purpose as a worm gear with a rack replacing the worm, in that both convert torque to linear force.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] However the rack and pinion generally provides higher linear speed — since a full turn of the pinion displaces the rack by an amount equal to the pinion's pitch circle whereas a full rotation of the worm screw only displaces the rack by one tooth width.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] By the same token, a rack and pinion mechanism yields a smaller linear force than a worm gear, for the same input torque.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] Also, a rack and pinion pair can be used in the opposite way, to turn linear force into torque; whereas a worm drive can be used in only one way.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] The teeth of a rack and pinion pair may be either straight (parallel to the rotation axis, as in a spur gear) or helical.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] On the pinion, the profile of the working tooth surfaces is usually an arc of involute, as in most gears.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] On the rack, on the other hand, the matching working surfaces are flat.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] One may interpret them as involute tooth faces for a gear with infinite radius.
[src:linear-actuators/rack-and-pinion] In both parts the teeth are typically formed with a gear cutter (a hob).
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] A **roller screw**, also known as a **planetary roller screw** or **satellite roller screw**, is a low-friction precision screw-type actuator, a mechanical device for converting rotational motion to linear motion, or vice versa.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Planetary roller screws are used as the actuating mechanism in many electromechanical linear actuators.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Due to its complexity, the roller screw is a relatively expensive actuator (as much as an order of magnitude more expensive than ball screws), but may be suitable for high-precision, high-speed, heavy-load, long-life, and heavy-use applications.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Roller screw mechanisms are commonly incorporated into motion/positioning systems in a variety of industries such as manufacturing and aerospace.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] More recently, planetary roller screws have been adopted by humanoid robotics manufacturers, such as in the linear actuators of the Tesla Optimus, due to their ability to withstand high shock loads during dynamic movement.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] A roller screw is a mechanical actuator similar to a ball screw, but which uses rollers as the load transfer elements between nut and screw instead of balls.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The rollers are typically threaded but may also be grooved depending on roller screw type.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Providing more bearing points than ball screws within a given volume, roller screws can be more compact for a given load capacity while providing similar efficiency (75%-90%) at low-to-moderate speeds, and maintain relatively high efficiency at high speeds.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Roller screws can surpass ball screws in regard to positioning precision, load rating, rigidity, speed, acceleration, and lifetime.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Standard roller screw actuators can achieve dynamic load ratings above 130 tons of force (exceeded in single-unit actuator capacity only by hydraulic cylinders).
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The three main elements of a typical planetary roller screw are the screw shaft, the nut, and the planetary roller.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The screw, a shaft with a multi-start V-shaped thread, provides a helical raceway for multiple rollers radially arrayed around the screw and encapsulated by a threaded nut.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The thread of the screw is typically identical to the internal thread of the nut.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The rollers spin in contact with, and serve as low-friction transmission elements between, screw and nut.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The rollers typically have a single-start thread with convex flanks that limit friction at the rollers' contacts with screw and nut.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The rollers typically orbit the screw as they spin (in the manner of planet gears to sun gear), and are thus known as planetary, or satellite, rollers.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] As with a lead screw or ball screw, rotation of the nut results in screw travel, and rotation of the screw results in nut travel.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] For a given screw diameter and quantity of thread starts, more rollers correspond to higher static load capacity, but not necessarily to a higher dynamic load capacity.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Preloaded split nuts and double nuts are available to eliminate backlash.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Carl Bruno Strandgren developed some of the earliest effective forms of roller screws and applied for a patent in Nice, France in February 1942.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The French patent #888.281 was granted in August 1943 and published in December of the same year.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The first commercial roller screw was designed and manufactured under his supervision in 1949 and was mounted on a narrow-gauge locomotive which operated in a northern France coal mine.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Subsequent units were produced and mounted on machine tools and (starting in 1955) on aircraft.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] At that time, Strandgren applied for a new patent incorporating detailed calculations and detailed manufacturing considerations, for which he was awarded US patents for such a “Screw-Threaded Mechanism” in 1954, and “Nut and Screw Devices” and the "Roller Screw" in 1965.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Roller screw types are defined by the motion of the rollers relative to the nut and screw.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The four commercially available types of roller screw are *standard*, *inverted*, *recirculating*, and *bearing ring*.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Now that the core patents have expired, an open source roller screw was developed in OpenSCAD to be 3-D printed for food processing applications.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The planetary roller screw can be fabricated in dishwasher-safe polyethylene terephthalate glycol (PETG) on any desktop 3-D printer.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The maximum force is more than doubled for the roller screw actuator using the same materials when compared to a direct screw press, making them adequate for some food processing techniques.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The standard planetary roller screw is also known as the non-recirculating roller screw.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The lack of axial movement of the roller relative to the nut, and the gearing of rollers to nut, are definitive of the standard type of roller screw.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The nut and screw have identical multiple-start threads.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The rollers have a single-start thread with an angle matching the nut thread.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The matched thread angle prevents axial movement between the nut and the roller as the rollers spin.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The nut assembly includes spacer rings and ring gears that position and guide the rollers.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The spacer rings, which rotate within the ring gears, have equidistant holes that act as rotary bearings for the smooth pivot ends (studs) of the rollers.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The ring gears time the spinning and orbit of the rollers about the screw axis by engaging gear teeth near the ends of the rollers.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The spacer rings rotate on axis with the screw in unison with the orbit of the rollers.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The spacer rings float relative to the nut, axially secured by retaining rings, because they spin around the screw at a lower frequency (angular velocity) than the nut.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Standard roller screws are typically identified by screw diameter (typically ranging from 3.5mm – 200mm) and lead (1mm – 62mm).
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The threading of the screw (3 – 6 starts) is either rolled (lower capacity) or ground (higher capacity).
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The diameters of the nut and rollers (7 – 14 in quantity) are simple functions of the screw diameter and lead.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] For example, if the screw diameter is 30 mm, the lead is 20 mm, and there are 5 thread starts, then the rollers have a diameter of 10 mm, the thread pitch is 4 mm, and the nut has a 50 mm effective diameter.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The inverted planetary roller screw is also known as the reverse roller screw.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The lack of axial movement of the roller relative to the screw, and the gearing of rollers to screw, are definitive of the inverted type of planetary roller screw.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] This type of roller screw was developed simultaneously with the standard roller screw.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Inverted roller screws operate on the same principles of standard roller screws except that the function of the nut and screw is reversed in relation to the rollers.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The rollers move axially within the nut, which is elongated to accommodate the full extent of screw shaft travel.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The threaded portion of the screw shaft is limited to the threaded length of the rollers.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The non-threaded portion of the screw shaft can be a smooth or non-cylindrical shape.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The ring gear is replaced by gear teeth above and below the threaded portion of the screw shaft.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Aside from the inversion of the relationship of rollers to nut and screw, the configuration and relationships of inverted roller screws match those of standard roller screws.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The recirculating type of planetary roller screw is also known as a recycling roller screw.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] A recirculating roller screw can provide a very high degree of positional accuracy by using minimal thread leads.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The rollers of a recirculating roller screw move axially within the nut until being reset after one orbit about the screw.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Recirculating roller screws do not employ ring gears.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Carl Bruno Strandgren was awarded a US Patent for the recirculating roller screw in 1965.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The screw and nut may have very fine identical single- or two-start threads.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Recirculating rollers are grooved (instead of threaded) so that they move axially during spinning engagement with the threads of the nut and screw, shifting up or down by one lead of thread after completing an orbit around the screw.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The nut assembly typically includes a slotted cage and cam rings.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The cage captivates the rollers in elongated slots, equally spacing the rollers while permitting rotation and axial motion of the rollers.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The cam rings have opposing cams aligned with an axial groove in the wall of the nut.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] After a roller completes an orbit about the nut it is released into the groove, disengages from nut and screw, and is pushed between the cams to the axial midpoint of the nut assembly (shifting by a distance equal to the lead of the screw).
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Returned to its starting position, and reengaged to nut and screw, the roller may then orbit the screw once again.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Lawlor received a patent for a cageless recirculating roller screw system.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] As with the traditional recirculating roller screw system, rollers disengage from the screw when they come upon an axial groove in the wall of the nut.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The system differs in that the rollers are continually engaged by the nut, and the axial groove of the nut is threaded.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Non-helical threads in the axial groove of the nut return the roller to its axial starting position (after completion of an orbit).
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Non-circular compression rings, or cam rings, at opposite ends of the rollers (roller axles) apply constant pressure between rollers and nut, synchronizing roller rotation and thrusting the rollers into the nut's axial groove.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Lacking ring gears and roller cage, cageless recirculating roller screws can be relatively efficient and, as a result, permit higher dynamic capacities for some screw shaft diameters.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] In 1986 Oliver Saari was awarded a patent for a bearing ring roller screw, commonly referred to by its trademark, Spiracon.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] This type matches the orbit of the rollers to the rotation of the nut assembly.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The actuator contains more load transfer elements than the other types, a bearing ring and thrust bearings, but manufacture of component parts is relatively simple (e.g. gearing teeth may be eliminated).
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] In the other roller screw types above, loads are transferred from the nut through the rollers to the screw (or in the reverse order).
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] In this type of actuator, thrust bearings and a freely rotating internally grooved bearing ring transfer loads between the rollers and the nut.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The rollers and encapsulating rotating ring are identically grooved, not threaded, so there is no axial movement between the two.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The nut assembly includes a cylindrical housing capped by non-rotating spacer rings.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The spacer rings have equidistant holes that act as rotary bearings for the smooth pivot ends (studs) of the rollers.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Roller-type thrust bearings between the spacer rings and bearing ring permit free rotation of the bearing ring while transferring the axial load between the two.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The rollers act as the “threads” of the nut assembly, causing axial movement of the rotating screw due to their orbital restraint.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Screw rotation spins the rollers, which spin the bearing ring, dissipating the load-induced friction along the way.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] Erhart was awarded a US patent in 1996 for a linear actuator effectively incorporating an inverted bearing ring roller screw.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The screw shaft is grooved the length of and to match the grooved rollers, which travel with the shaft.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The bearing ring is elongated and internally threaded for the length of screw shaft travel.
[src:linear-actuators/roller-screw] The nut assembly housing and sealed end ring forms the exterior of the actuator assembly.
